{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566193"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:36:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:36:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18704"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18704"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.03,0.35,0.02,0.59]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11436"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76968"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11436"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18704"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62473"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"201"},{"type":"tags","id":"205"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11213"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43702"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76968"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with three months of progressive shortness of breath and dry cough. He has a 15-year history of rheumatoid arthritis, treated with methotrexate and prednisolone, and type 2 diabetes managed with metformin. His other medications include folic acid and calcium/vitamin D supplements. He is an ex-smoker with a 30 pack-year history, having quit five years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly short of breath at rest. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There are bilateral fine crackles at both lung bases. His hands show typical rheumatoid changes with ulnar deviation and swan-neck deformities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest X-ray shows bilateral reticular shadowing in the lower zones.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary embolism","Heart failure","Methotrexate-induced pneumonitis","Community-acquired pneumonia","Connective tissue disease-associated interstitial lung disease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of rheumatoid arthritis-associated interstitial lung disease (RA-ILD), which is a form of \u003Cstrong\u003Econnective tissue disease-associated interstitial lung disease\u003C/strong\u003E. The gradual onset of dyspnoea and dry cough, along with bilateral fine crackles and radiological changes in a patient with long-standing rheumatoid arthritis is characteristic. Risk factors include male sex, smoking history, and long-standing disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate-induced pneumonitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a controversial diagnosis that has been the subject of ongoing debate. While traditionally described as presenting acutely within the first year of treatment with fever and hypersensitivity-like features, there is significant overlap with RA-ILD symptoms and imaging findings. Some experts argue that historical cases of \u0027methotrexate lung\u0027 may have actually represented progression of underlying RA-ILD. The relationship between methotrexate and lung disease is further complicated by evidence suggesting methotrexate may actually be protective against RA-ILD progression in some patients. Current evidence suggests true methotrexate pneumonitis is rare.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommunity-acquired pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents more acutely with fever and productive cough. While patients on methotrexate have an increased risk of pulmonary infections due to immunosuppression, the chronic progression and bilateral nature of the findings make this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute onset dyspnoea and pleuritic chest pain. While patients with RA have an increased risk of venous thromboembolism, the chronic progression and examination findings are not consistent with PE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeart failure\u003C/strong\u003E could present with similar symptoms, and patients with RA have a two to three-fold increased risk of cardiovascular disease compared to the general population. However, the presence of bilateral fine crackles (rather than dependent crackles) and the radiological pattern is more consistent with interstitial lung disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERA-ILD is a serious complication occurring in approximately 10% of patients with rheumatoid arthritis. The usual interstitial pneumonia (UIP) pattern is most common, followed by non-specific interstitial pneumonia (NSIP). Management typically involves immunosuppression, and the condition significantly impacts prognosis. The decision to continue or withdraw methotrexate in cases of progressive lung disease should be individualised, considering the possibility that methotrexate may be beneficial in some cases by controlling underlying RA activity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rheumatoid arthritis-associated interstitial lung disease typically presents with progressive dyspnoea and dry cough in patients with established RA.","Risk factors for RA-ILD include smoking history, male sex, and high rheumatoid factor titres.","Bilateral fine crackles (velcro crackles) on chest examination are characteristic of interstitial lung disease.","Distinguishing between methotrexate pneumonitis and RA-ILD can be challenging as they share similar clinical and radiological features."],"references":["Jee AS, Sheehy R, Hopkins P, Corte TJ, Grainge C, Troy LK, Symons K, Spencer LM, Reynolds PN, Chapman S, De Boer S. Diagnosis and management of connective tissue disease\u2010associated interstitial lung disease in Australia and New Zealand: a position statement from the Thoracic Society of Australia and New Zealand. Respirology. 2021 Jan;26(1):23-51. Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/resp.13977","Fragoulis GE, Nikiphorou E, Larsen J, Korsten P, Conway R. Methotrexate-associated pneumonitis and rheumatoid arthritis-interstitial lung disease: current concepts for the diagnosis and treatment. Frontiers in medicine. 2019 Oct 23;6:238."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62473"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18704"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62473"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T20:59:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T21:01:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11436"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76968"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagG